s is reported","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The parsing logic itself (try-catch, increment counter) could be unit-tested in isolation. But the phrase 'without crashing the pipeline' implies testing the full pipeline end-to-end. A unit test of just the JSON parser might miss downstream integration failures: exceptions not propagating correctly, state not being updated, or the pipeline continuing but in a corrupted state. A mock parser could pass all unit tests yet fail when wired into the real pipeline with real concurrency or message flow. The *failure boundary* is the interaction between error handling and the rest of the system.","test_description":"Create a mock or test input stream (e.g., a list or in-memory queue) with mixed valid and malformed JSON entries: valid entries, null bytes, truncated JSON, non-UTF-8, deeply nested objects, etc. Feed the entire stream into the full processing pipeline (not just the parser in isolation). Verify: (1) malformed entries are skipped gracefully, (2) valid entries are processed, (3) the skipped count is accurate and reported, (4) the pipeline continues processing after encountering malformed data, (5) no unhandled exceptions propagate.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Performance under load requires testing with real I/O patterns, real concurrency, and real timing. A unit test of the parsing function with in-memory data won't catch bottlenecks in file reading, JSON parsing, memory allocation, or buffer management. A mock might represent 10K entries, but processing them in microseconds on the test thread is not representative. An integration test with a local file or in-memory queue, wired into the full tool with real buffering and concurrency, can measure throughput and verify no drops. System testing (real network I/O, real subprocess) would be even more realistic but is not strictly necessary if the bottleneck is local processing. The minimum is Integration: real I/O patterns + real concurrency on local infrastructure.","test_description":"Prepare a test input with 100K+ log entries (local file or in-memory queue). Run the tool against this input while measuring throughput, monitoring for dropped entries (via checksums or sequence numbers), and tracking end-to-end latency. Verify the tool sustains ≥10K entries/sec for at least 10 seconds without: (1) dropping or skipping entries, (2) accumulating unbounded queue depth or latency (falling behind), (3) excessive memory growth or CPU usage. Include concurrent sinks (e.g., multiple output streams) to simulate real parallel processing.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.46,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13906,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13906},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"636646ff-b557-4a85-99ad-504605118e2a","uuid":"f2e1ae0c-70f6-47d9-9954-339ffd763d33"}
